<page_title>Difference electronic structure has different absorption and emission spectrum</page_title>
<text>  Different Substances Have Different Photon Absorptions and Emissions
p. 5 of 8
&lt; Previous | Index | Next &gt;

Each atom or molecule has its own unique distribution of energy levels, which is called its electronic structure (or electron configuration).  The electronic structure of a system is very important to its properties.  One way to measure electronic structures is to shine a beam of white light through the sample and to measure what wavelengths of light are absorbed. White light is a mix of photons of all possible energies. 

The atoms in the model window below each have five electronic energy levels, represented by the four black lines and one blue line in the energy level diagram to the right of the model window.

1) Click the Run button to start a parade of photons.  Let it run for at least two to three minutes.  Below the simulator, spectral lines representing photon absorptions should begin to appear.  As the model is running, answer Question A before moving on to step 2.
2) Click Stop.  Then take snapshots of both the energy level diagram and the absorption spectrum by right-clicking (or control-clicking) on each and selecting Take a Snapshot.
3) Click the Reset button.  Then click Yes when asked if you really want to reset to the saved state.
4) Now add about 4 or 5 more energy levels by double clicking on any of the tick marks on the energy level diagram (new black lines should appear after each double click).
5) Click the Run button to start another parade of photons.  Let it run for at least two minutes.  Below the simulator, spectral lines representing photon absorptions should begin to appear.  As the model is running, answer Question B before moving on to step 6.
6) Click Stop.  Then take snapshots of both the energy level diagram and the absorption spectrum by right-clicking (or control-clicking) on each and selecting Take a Snapshot.



  

   
