Energy
 
Color Conventions of Spectra:  Absorption spectra will be recorded in the strip above.  The strip has a background of a continuous white-color spectrum (called continuum spectrum, the rainbow of colors).  When the simulation begins, black lines will appear which represent the energies of absorbed light. The background for the invisible zones (infrared and ultraviolet) are white.  The black lines can also be thought of as the energy of the absorbed photons. 
  

 

 

Because each substance has a unique electronic structure and its absorption spectrum (of visible light) is solely determined by the electronic structure, a spectrum can be used to identify a substance, just as a fingerprint can be used to identify a person. Once the spectrum of an unknown substance is obtained, we can compare it against those of known substances. If a match is found, then the composition of the substance may be inferred. This technique is widely used in astronomy to determine the composition of stellar matter. The details of spectrum analysis is beyond the scope of our models.


